title: For Sale:  Spikes Tactical AR-15, Never Fired
postcontent:
Brand new, never fired, serial #0080.  Spikes are considered Tier One quality.  Local sale only, must have copy of NC state ID.  Also have available a Vortex Strikefire optic, $165 and 6 aluminum 30 round mags, $20 each.  Call or text NINE 1 0, two two 4, 9579.

Here is some info courtesy of a post on zombiehunters.org:

If you don't understand the difference between a "Hobby Grade" AR15 and a "TIER ONE" AR15 you should research the following topics:

* (Tier One) vs (Hobby Grade)

* Milspec 7075 Forged .148" Receiver Extension vs Commercial 6061 Extruded .168/.170" Receiver Extension
* Staked vs Non Staked Castle Nuts
* Forged 7075-T6 Lower Receiver vs Cast or Polymer Lower Receivers
* 1/7 Twist Rate vs 1/8 or 1/9 Twist Rate
* 5.56x45mm Chamber vs 223 Remington Chamber
* Chrome Lined Bore & Chamber vs Non Chromed Lined Bore and Chamber
* Certified Mil-B-11595E Barrel Steel vs 4140 or Non-Certified 4150 Barrel Steel
* M4 Feed Ramps vs M16 Feed Ramps
* F-Marked Front Sight Base vs Non F-Marked Front Sight Base
* Tapered FSB Pins vs Straight FSB Pins
* Parkerzing Under FSB vs Bare Steel Under FSB
* Every Barrel Being High-Pressure / Magnetic Particle Inspected vs "Batch" Testing
* Every Bolt Being HP / MPI vs "Batch" Testing
* Shot Peened Bolt vs Not Shot Peened Bolts
* M16 Bolt Carrier vs AR15 Bolt Carrier
* 158 Carpenter Steel Bolt Carriers vs Other Bolt Carrier Materials
* Chrome Lined Bolt Carrier vs Non Chrome Lined Bolt Carrier
* Chrome Lined Gas Key vs Non Chrome Lined Gas Key
* Properly Staked Gas Key vs Improperly Staked Gas Key
* Grade 8 GK Screws vs Anything Else
* Black Bolt Extractor Inserts vs Blue Bolt Extractor Inserts
* Tool Steel Extractors vs MIM Extractors
* H Buffers vs Carbine Buffers

If you want the best from your rifle you need to have everything on the "left side" of the above issues.

title: For Sale:  Japanese Type I Rifle - Carcano Made, WW2 - 6.5x50
postcontent:
Japanese Type I rifle.  These were comissioned from Italian gunmaker Carcano for the Japanese Empire before WW2 (1937-1939), and issued to the Japanese Navy in the pacific theatre.  Somewhere between 60,000 and 120,000 of them were built.  Very interesting bolt-action rifle chambered in 6.5x50 Arisaka.  Internal box 5-shot magazine (loads with 5-rd stripper clips).  Has very few markings, but appears to be almost complete. This has a bent bolt-handle brazed on (originals were a straight bolt).  It also has an aftermarket stock ("sporterized").  

Rear elevation flip-up sight is marked for 500-2400 yards/meters...yes...over a mile and a half.  Its a long shot on the open Ocean I guess.  It looks rediculous when you adjust it to 2400 and aim...just flat our crazy.

These are uncommon in the US market.  Gun appears to function fine, bolt cycles, safety works, etc.  Barrel looks to be in great shape.  Many of these were brought back as "war trophies" from the Kwajalein Atoll, the Philippines, or from Japan.

Sold as-is with 15-rounds of ammunition. Many more pictures available (email me for a link). Can be seen in person M-F 6am-5pm near US-131 & M-6 on the south side of Grand Rapids. 

Asking $250 obo (with case). $225 obo without case.
